From 6ffed769df6db563aef28c0b946fa4594608d342 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: utzcoz <utzcoz@outlook.com>
Date: Wed, 1 Jul 2026 00:07:57 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] vr: run the OpenXR XR Device Service sandboxed on Linux

The XR Device Service hosts the OpenXR loader, which resolves the active
runtime manifest (active_runtime.json), dlopen()s the runtime library it
names (e.g. libopenxr_monado.so), connects to the runtime's per-user IPC
socket, and creates an in-process Vulkan instance to render into. On Linux
the service ran as a generic kUtility process with no pre-sandbox hook and
no broker, so none of that worked under the sandbox and the OpenXR path
required --no-sandbox.

Give the XR Device Service its own sandbox on Linux, modelled on the
Windows kXrCompositing type and the kSpeechRecognition pre-sandbox hook:

- Enable the kXrCompositing sandbox enum value and the kXrSandbox service
  constant on Linux (sandbox.mojom, isolated_xr_service.mojom), make the
  type round-trip through the command line (sandbox_type.cc), and accept
  it in the browser-side launcher DCHECK (utility_sandbox_delegate.cc).

- Fork the service from the unsandboxed zygote (utility_sandbox_delegate.cc
  GetZygote), like the other hook-based services, so the broker is created
  before the process is namespaced. The pre-sandboxed generic zygote
  namespaces the child first, which makes the broker's single-threaded
  fork check read an unavailable /proc and abort.

- Add content/utility/xr/xr_sandbox_hook_linux.cc, a pre-sandbox hook that
  starts a syscall broker granting read access to the OpenXR manifest
  search paths, the runtime library and its dependency closure, the Vulkan
  ICD, and read-write access to the DRM render nodes plus the GPU's sysfs
  entries (the runtime creates its own Vulkan instance in-process). It does
  not engage the namespace sandbox: the runtime must reach the compositor's
  host AF_UNIX socket, which a network namespace would cut off.

- Add sandbox/policy/linux/bpf_xr_policy_linux.cc (XrProcessPolicy): the GPU
  process policy (the runtime renders with Vulkan) plus the AF_UNIX socket
  syscalls the runtime uses to reach its compositor and pass DMA-BUF / sync
  fds over it. socket() is restricted to AF_UNIX.

- Guard OpenXrRenderLoop::SubmitFrameDrawnIntoTexture() against a frame that
  arrives after StopRuntime() has reset context_provider_, matching the
  existing null check in OnWebXrTokenSignaled().

With the base zygote sandbox enabled, the OpenXR path no longer needs
--no-sandbox.

Verified end to end against Monado without --no-sandbox (AppArmor profile
for the dev binary, DCHECK build): the sandbox engages, the XR utility runs
as --service-sandbox-type=xr_compositing, the broker forks, the loader
reaches active_runtime.json and loads libopenxr_monado.so, xrCreateInstance
connects to Monado, the in-process Vulkan instance/device is created, the
immersive-vr session starts, the swapchain format is negotiated, and frames
are submitted to Monado.
